    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1954-07-02T06:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1954-07-02T06:00:00-05:00" n="1014"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1014">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">751G.5 <gloss target="#t_MSP1">MSP</gloss>/7–254:
                    Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé at Saigon</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_MR2"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">McClintock</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Department of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Saigon</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1954-07-02T19:00:00+08:00"
                            >July 2, 1954—7 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>25. Repeated information Hanoi 7. For some time past both Embassy and <gloss
                        target="#t_MAAG1">MAAG</gloss> have vigorously pressed with French matter of
                    supplying arms to Governor <persName corresp="#p_NHT1">Tri</persName>’s militia
                    with little result as set forth in Hanoi’s reports. Problem has developed into
                    all too familiar pattern where Governor <persName corresp="#p_NHT1"
                        >Tri</persName> appeals to Consulate and Embassy, <gloss target="#t_MAAG1"
                        >MAAG</gloss> and Embassy put pressure on French, French promise action, and
                        <persName corresp="#p_NHT1">Tri</persName> still does not get his guns.</p>
                <p>After so many unproductive approaches to French, <gloss target="#t_MAAG1"
                        >MAAG</gloss> and Embassy now believe that matter rests between French and
                        <persName corresp="#p_NHT1">Tri</persName> and that question has moved from
                    one of straight supply of equipment to <pb facs="0392" n="1774" xml:id="pg_1774"
                    /> political problem where we are faced with apparent French decision to
                    withhold arms. With deteriorating situation in north and with withdrawal of
                    French forces from large areas of delta to limited defense perimeter, it will be
                    increasingly difficult to argue against possible French contention that rifles
                    now delivered to militia will probably soon fall into Viet Minh hands.</p>
                <p>In light of above, Embassy and <gloss target="#t_MAAG1">MAAG</gloss> believe it
                    unwise to further pressure French on the matter.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_MR2">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">McClintock</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
